  "text": "We claim that f (V ) \u2282 C \\ f (\u2202V ). On the contrary, let z \u2208 V \u2229 K f such that f (z) \u2208 f (\u2202V ). If z \u2208 U , a Fatou component, denote by c the center of U . Since \u2202V \u2229 K f consists of internal rays and z \u2208 V , then, if z = c, the entire U is contained in V ; otherwise, there is a unique internal ray of U passing through z, which is contained Figure 5 . The decomposition of [z, w] and its image in [CITATION_1] in V \u222a {c}. Anyway, we can pick an internal ray r z of U with r z \u2282 V \u222a {c}. So, by choosing the landing point of r z if necessary, we can assume z \u2208 J f . In this case, there is an external ray contained in f (\u2202V ) landing at f (z), and its lift based at z is also an external ray. As z \u2208 V , all external rays landing at z belong to V \u2229 U (\u221e). It contradicts to the fact that f (V \u2229 U (\u221e)) = U (\u221e) \\ f (\u2202V ). The claim is then proven. Now, we fix a point w W \u2208 U (\u221e) in each component W of C \\ f (\u2202V ) and denote by z W the unique preimage of w W in V \u2229 U (\u221e). Given any connected component W of C \\ f (\u2202V ), and any point w \u2208 W , we pick an arc \u03b3 w \u2282 W joining w and w W . We assert that \u03b3 w has a unique lift in V starting from z W . Firstly, let \u0393 denote the component of f \u22121 (\u03b3 w ) that contains z W . Then \u0393 \u2282 V since z W \u2208 V and \u03b3 w \u2229 f (\u2202V ) = \u2205. Note also that V contains no critical points of f , so f : \u0393 \u2192 \u03b3 w is a covering, and hence a homeomorphism. We denote by h(w) the end point of this lift. Since W is simplyconnected, the point h(w) is independent on the choice of \u03b3 w . We then get a map h : C \\ f (\u2202V ) \u2192 V . This map is easily checked to be the inverse of f : V \u2192 C \\ f (\u2202V ). (3) Let z, w be two distinct points in V \u2229 K f with f (z) = f (w). We first claim that both z and w belong to \u22